SIX life sentences and 46 years in prison!That is the sentence handed down to a Nelson Mandela Bay human trafficker at the Uitenhage Regional Court yesterday. She was convicted in October. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Nombuyiselo Matiti (52) was found guilty on 12 counts, including racketeering, sexual exploitation of a child and of a mentally disabled person.She was also handed a further 10-year suspended sentence. Her accomplice Nolubabalo Mboya (27) was sentenced to five years of correctional supervision.The two lured three mentally disabled girls, pupils at a special school in Uitenhage, to Port Elizabeth promising them jobs. For several months, the girls were kept sedated and locked in a room at a brothel while being sexually exploited. Several kids were rescued in July 2012 in a raid on a house at Hlathini squatter camp. Magistrate John Montgomery said: “Matiti is a danger to society. She used girls that trusted her as a mother and made money by prostituting them.”Meanwhile, the Blue Bulls U- 21 rugby player accused of rape was granted R10 000 bail in the New Brighton Magistrates Court.